protego.title: Protego
protego.home.subheader: Deploy machine learning models capable of detecting SQL injection payloads
protego.home.p: Malicious software, or malware, has quickly become a top threat among companies and government agencies. It has the potential to expose sensitive information, halt business operations, and even cause a catastrophic loss of life. Malware can be deployed in many ways including hardware injection (USB), software injection, and misconfiguration. Software injection continues to be a popular attack vector and consistently ranks within the top three web application security risks published by OWASP. One of the simplest types of software injection is called SQL injection. This attack takes advantage of the fact that most applications interact with a database. Engineers can reduce the risk of successful attacks by following secure development practices, but cannot eliminate them. Protego is an easy-to-use Python package that can be leveraged to identify and deter SQL injection attacks. It uses the most current machine learning algorithms to identify attacks with high accuracy.

protego.docs.section3.intro: Start detecting SQL injection attempts today! Create workgroups, review and label data, and develop your own machine learning models. Predictions can be made from any application with a simple API call.
protego.docs.section3.h3.p: Define groups, assign group members, and generate API tokens here.
protego.docs.section3.h3.h4.1.p: Any user can create their own groups. By default, the creator of a group is the group administrator. Only group administrators can add, modify, and delete groups, group members, and API tokens. Group members, API tokens, models, and payloads are children of groups. Deleting a group will delete all children.
protego.docs.section3.h3.h4.2.p: Involve your team! Group members can create, train, test, and delete machine learning models. In addition, they can review, edit, and delete payloads. This may include labeling or removing samples.
protego.docs.section3.h3.h4.3.p: API tokens are required to use the Protego API. Simply pass the valid token in your request header. If an API token is expired, a new one must be generated.
protego.docs.section3.h3.2.p: Create model instances here. Models follow two paradigms, online learning and batch learning. Options include
protego.docs.section3.h3.3.p: Edit and delete data here. These samples are used train models. Prior to training on any of these samples, classifications should be reviewed and accurately labeled. Want to get started sooner? Select the 'Load delivered payloads here' link. This will load approximately 115k samples that are delivered with the application.
protego.docs.section3.h3.4.p: Train instantiated models here. Select a payload range to use for training and select the 'Train' button. You also have the option to delete payloads used for training from the database by setting 'Purge Payloads' to yes.
protego.docs.section3.h3.5.p: Experiment with trained models here. You can test on a single sample or a batch of samples.
